Reactive oxygen species and aging: evolving questions.

Dugan LL(1), Quick KL.

Author information:
(1)Division of General Medicine and Geriatrics, Department of Medicine, 
University of California, San Diego, La Jolla, CA 92093, USA. ladugan@ucsd.edu

Over the past 50 years, reactive oxygen species (ROS) have been investigated as 
putative mediators of the process of aging. As specific genes and pathways that 
are involved with ROS homeostasis have been linked to aging in lower organisms, 
such as Caenorhabditis elegans and Drosophila, the questions of how ROS regulate 
aging in higher organisms, and whether they do so to the same extent as in lower 
organisms, have emerged.

